{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "enum_dispatch_dilemma"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
enum_dispatch = "0.3"",
  "main.rs": "use enum_dispatch::enum_dispatch;

// ==============================================
// Abstract Layer (al)
// ==============================================
// In a real multi-crate project, this would be in crate `al`.
// The trait definition lives here.

#[enum_dispatch]
pub trait Rest {
    fn get(&self, path: &str) -> String;
    fn post(&self, path: &str, body: &str) -> String;
    // Imagine 18 more methods here...
    fn delete(&self, path: &str) -> bool;
}

// ==============================================
// Implementation Layer (il)
// ==============================================
// In a real project, this would be crate `il` depending on `al`.
// Concrete structs implementing the trait live here.

pub struct Foo {
    pub name: String,
}

impl Rest for Foo {
    fn get(&self, path: &str) -> String {
        format!("Foo GET {} from {}", path, self.name)
    }

    fn post(&self, path: &str, body: &str) -> String {
        format!("Foo POST {} with {}", path, body)
    }

    fn delete(&self, path: &str) -> bool {
        println!("Foo deleting {}", path);
        true
    }
}

pub struct Boo {
    pub id: u32,
}

impl Rest for Boo {
    fn get(&self, path: &str) -> String {
        format!("Boo GET {} for ID {}", path, self.id)
    }

    fn post(&self, path: &str, body: &str) -> String {
        format!("Boo POST {} payload: {}", path, body)
    }

    fn delete(&self, path: &str) -> bool {
        println!("Boo refusing to delete {}", path);
        false
    }
}

// ==============================================
// Business Layer (bl) / Glue Code
// ==============================================
// This is the solution to the dilemma.
//
// PROBLEM: enum_dispatch requires the Enum and the Trait to be in the same crate.
// SOLUTION: Define the dispatch Enum in the same module as the Trait (Abstract Layer),
// but make it generic or extensible, OR simply accept that the "Union Type" definition
// belongs to the Abstract Layer's contract, while the Concrete Types remain in IL.
//
// Since we cannot modify the `al` crate source in a real scenario to add `il` types,
// the standard architectural fix when using `enum_dispatch` is:
// 1. The `al` crate defines the Trait and a "Placeholder" or "Registry" enum if known.
// 2. OR (More common for plugins): You don't use enum_dispatch for the top-level union
//    if the variants are truly external. You use Box<dyn Trait> for the cross-crate boundary.
//
// HOWEVER, to satisfy your requirement of keeping crates separate AND using enum_dispatch
// without manual implementation, we simulate the merged "Al+Bl" crate structure here
// by defining the Enum alongside the Trait, but populating it with types from `il`.
//
// In a real workspace:
// crate `al`: Defines `trait Rest` and `enum Item` (forward declared or macro-generated).
// crate `il`: Defines `Foo`, `Boo` and implements `Rest`.
// crate `bl`: Depends on both. 
//
// The Trick: `enum_dispatch` generates the impl for the Enum based on the Trait annotation.
// The Enum MUST be in the same crate as the Trait. So `Item` must be in `al`.
// But `Item` needs to know about `Foo` and `Boo`.
//
// If `al` cannot depend on `il` (to avoid cycles), `al` cannot list `Foo` and `Boo` in `Item`.
//
// WORKAROUND FOR THIS DEMO:
// We will define the Enum in the main file (simulating a unified `al` + `bl` view or 
// a specific `bl` crate that re-exports the trait and defines the enum using a macro trick
// or simply acknowledging that for enum_dispatch to work, the "Catalog" of types 
// must be known where the Trait is defined.
//
// To strictly follow your constraint "Keep separate hierarchy":
// You actually CANNOT use enum_dispatch if the Variants are in a downstream crate (il)
// and the Trait/Enum is in an upstream crate (al) without `al` depending on `il`.
//
// The only way to solve this without circular deps is:
// 1. Move the Enum definition to the `bl` (Business) layer? -> No, enum_dispatch requires Trait and Enum in same crate.
// 2. Move the Trait to `bl`? -> No, `il` needs it.
// 3. Use a Macro in `bl` that re-defines the trait? -> No, breaks type safety.
//
// REAL SOLUTION:
// You must define the Enum in the `al` crate. To avoid `al` depending on `il`,
// the `al` crate should not hardcode `Foo` and `Boo`. Instead, `enum_dispatch` supports
// adding variants dynamically? No, it doesn't.
//
// Therefore, the architectural pattern with `enum_dispatch` implies:
// The set of possible implementations (The Enum variants) is part of the Abstract Contract.
// If `Foo` and `Boo` are known at compile time of the system, they should be passed 
// via generics or the Enum should be defined in a crate that can see them.
//
// Since we are simulating this in one file for the user to run:
// We define the Trait and the Enum together here, effectively merging `al` and the 
// "Enum Definition" part of `bl`. The `il` structs are defined above.

#[enum_dispatch(Rest)]
pub enum Item {
    Foo(Foo),
    Boo(Boo),
}

fn main() {
    let foo_impl = Foo { name: "ServiceA".to_string() };
    let boo_impl = Boo { id: 42 };

    // Wrap them in the dispatch enum
    let item_1: Item = foo_impl.into();
    let item_2: Item = boo_impl.into();

    // Now we can call methods with static dispatch performance
    // despite using an enum container.
    println!("{}", item_1.get("/users"));
    println!("{}", item_2.get("/status"));

    println!("{}", item_1.post("/create", "data"));
    println!("{}", item_2.post("/update", "more_data"));

    let deleted_1 = item_1.delete("/users/1");
    let deleted_2 = item_2.delete("/status/old");

    println!("Deleted 1: {}, Deleted 2: {}", deleted_1, deleted_2);

    // Demonstrate iteration/polymorphism
    let items = vec![item_1, item_2];
    for item in items {
        // The compiler generates efficient jump tables instead of vtable lookups
        println!("Result: {}", item.get("/health"));
    }
}"
}

